Inflation, in Europe, has come to light on food
The accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was more important than the forecasts, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, indicating the European Community's statistics office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the United States, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not decrease the direct interest rate by saying that the decline in interest, with the rise in the prices of raw materials and the decline in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "Inflation must be discouraged" in order not to have any further action on this issue.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain, it is up from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has declined due to the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
The market rates for cereals increased by 88 per cent and soybean has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the global price of oil increased by 52 per cent and, last month, a silver barrel cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1, this year, to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009, it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the inflation rate of 12 months remains around 3 per cent, however, the annual average rate will be 2.1 per cent in the next 3 to 4 months.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the managerial rate twice in 2008.
