Many hospitals make the economy of disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
Hospital health conditions, insufficient number of beds, overcrowding of medical staff do not help to block infections, the doctor at the head of the National Centre for Epidemiology says.
Many hospitals also make the economy of disinfectants
There has been no long-term diagnosis of MRSA infection at the János hospital trauma service.
The antibiotic resistant bacteria were detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The disease has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injury of a serious car accident came out of the hospital but not long after it had to return because of a MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform an important operation due to the bacteria in their body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Monitoring System, said Karolina Böröcz, a doctor at the National Epidemiology Centre.
This is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, otherwise said by staphylococcus gold resistant to methyl oxylline-oxylline.
A third of the people are carriers of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as angina, amygdalitis, cutaneous infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, bacteria, which react well to antibiotics, will develop a well resistant bacteria that will quickly spread under poor hospital conditions.
In the case of temporary or prolonged immunosuppression, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicemia, on the elderly, small weights or with a weakened body.
According to hospital manager János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily hospital life.
In particular, there is no need to confuse infection with the epidemic, no MRSA is found only or not, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These diseases are isolated, the caring staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
In particular, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Taking the sample is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and residences for elderly people, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological extraction is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be known that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these reviews.
Most cases see only if MRSA infection is detectable on the disease, the doctor in charge of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the management of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, otherwise microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance but hospitals do not always take into account.
The realization of microbiological extracts is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals make the economy of disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, wear gloves and protective masks. However, important deficiencies are detected in hospitals in this area too.
However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in the end of the epidemic, the sick should be removed from each other at a minimum of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is less demonstrable or the proliferation of pathogen agent can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant costs for social security funds, which is why we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the Government has established a programme to prevent or reduce the impact of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) shows among its priorities the prevention of the impact of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
