British Army units report on the video-sharing site of their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to become popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has been passionate about YouTube: the special units involved in Afghanistan are charging video sequences on Taliban operations since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, with the help of mini-camera mounted on the helmet, are controlled in the general area of air force operations in Kandahar and are then transferred to London or the compatriots to the Internet.
The political message is irreversible
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been viewed by more than 75 thousand people.
The Department of British Defence has registered as "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 and reports videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on to the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to inform the public of the actual objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
The propaganda published by this route costs virtually nothing compared to the usual TV recruitment advertisements, which was communicated to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant. On the other hand, it also inevitably brings a political message, since it is in a special form justifying the well-founded military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have made a game
The army is embittered because, apart from the videos composed and censored carefully, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about losses, but they never present the bloody side of the battle.
In addition, many videos were already online presenting the operational areas in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army is only about to load these videos.
American recruits make it a little different by using America's Army free downloadable rifle game. In this game, the player can put himself directly in the position of soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
