A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen's Nazi archives, which portray the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are available free.
The 47 million archived documents, stored 27 km from a line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only to be consulted for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is to say, individually and nominee, on the request of an old victim or his rightholders.
The eleven States in charge of their management - Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the ratification process of this agreement has been completed by all States, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for research "in particular on the movement of prisoners, the population of camps and the health status of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, had opposed the opening to the public of these nominations because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some of the deportation victims.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, if possible, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are dealing with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to wait for these documents," said Pr Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Anti-Semitism Research at the Technische Universität de Berlin in 2006.
